              //- ANGULAR DYNAMIC CONTENT
              #lesson-module.container(ng-init='initiateQuiz()' data-topic='fluid_mechanics' data-lesson='buoyancy')
                .row
                  .col-sm-2
                  .col-sm-8
                    h1.page-header Buoyancy
                    p
                      | Let's consider now the interaction of solids and fluids. When a solid object is placed in a liquid, will it sink or will it float?
                    p
                      | Consider the solid at a moment when a part of it, the volume \( V_l \), has been submerged. Now imagine the solid was not present and replace the submerged part of the solid by liquid of the same volume, \( V_l \). The force of gravity on that
                      | volume of liquid is simply,
                    p
                      | $$ F_g^{liquid} = - m_d g = - V_l \rho_l g $$
                    p
                      | Where \( \rho_l \) is the density of the liquid. This configuration must be in equilibrium since \( V_l \) is the same liquid and the boundary drawn is entirely fictitious. So the force of gravity must be balanced by an upward force exerted
                      | on this volume by the rest of the liquid,
                    p
                      | $$ F_B^{liquid} = V_l \rho_l g $$
                    p
                      | But, the surrounding liquid could not known whether \( V_l \) is liquid or any other material. So, the upward force exerted on the solid by the surrounding liquid is the same,
                    p
                      | $$ F_B^{solid} = V_l \rho_l g $$
                    p
                      | This force is known as buoyancy. The force acting on the solid are then the buoyancy, \( F_B = V_l \rho_l g \) pushing it upwards, as well as its weight \( F_g = -m_{solid} g \) pulling it downwards. The volume, \( V_l \) is simply the volume
                      | of liquid displaced by the solid. Therefore, a simple way to state the law of buoyancy is to say that "buoyancy is equal to the weight of the liquid displaced by the solid". This is Archimedes' law.
                    canvas#buoyancy-force-chart(width='800' height='500')
                  .col-sm-2
